sec.p:
We used the fMRI data collected during the resting state to estimate general neural variability. Time series were extracted and split into nine non-overlapping windows with a length of 30 s. In space, we calculated the functional connectivity matrix within each window using Pearson’s correlation analysis. Each row (or each column) of the matrix represented the functional connectivity between a specific node and the remaining nodes across the whole brain. For each node, we compared the functional connectivity matrices across different windows of time using Pearson’s correlation analysis. General neural variability of the node was calculated by subtracting the mean of correlation coefficients from one. The following formula was used:
